sentences: Birgit Dieckmann, known professionally as Billie Ray Martin, is a German singer and songwriter, known for her single "Your Loving Arms", which reached the top 10 of both the UK Singles Chart (#6) and the Irish Singles Chart (#8) in 1995, and reached number one on the US Dance Club Chart.

She was also one of the vocalists on the S'Express UK top 10 hit single "Hey Music Lover" (1989), and had UK top 40 hits as lead vocalist of Electribe 101 with "Tell Me When the Fever Ended" (1989) and "Talking with Myself" (1990), and

"Talking with Myself" was re-mixed in 1998 and reached No. 39 in the UK charts.

In 2002, Sonnenstahl Records released the 12-track CD Recycled Garbage, a compilation of remixes of selected tracks from 18 Carat Garbage.
Solo: 2003–current ===
In 2003, Martin released a series of singles on her new Disco Activisto label, including the electronic music club hits "No Brakes on My Rollerskates" and "Dead Again".
In 2005–06 she released collaborations with DJ Hell and Slam.
The Moroder-influenced solo single "Undisco Me" was released on Rebirth Records in April 2007, and reached No. 6 in the UK Dance Chart.
In 2008, Martin formed a new band, The Opiates, with Robert Solheim producing.
In 2010, she released The Crackdown Project featuring her takes on the Cabaret Voltaire classic album, The Crackdown.
2011 began with the solo single "Sweet Suburban Disco".
A second EP from The Opiates, titled Rainy Days and Remixes, was released in September 2011 as a prelude to their album Hollywood Under The Knife.
In February 2012, a remix collection entitled Hollywood Cuts was released.
2012 saw the release of a series of collaborations including "Make Me Feel" on Terranova's Hotel Amour album, and "Hyper Lust" on the new album from Motor.

In the early 1980s, Billie Ray Martin moved to Berlin.
After these experiences, Billie Ray Martin moved to London, where she placed an ad in Melody Maker reading "soul rebel seeks musical genius".
The ad led to a meeting with four men from Birmingham who had been looking for a voice to add to their music, resulting in the formation of Electribe 101.
"Talking with Myself" remains a club classic and has appeared on countless Ibiza and chill-out compilations over the past 22 years.
A live concert at London's The Town & Country Club (now The London Forum) was televised on ITV to coincide with the album's release.
Electribe 101 were then selected as the supporting act for the European leg of Depeche Mode’s 'World Violation' tour, including several nights at both the Birmingham NEC and Wembley Arena.
BRM's debut solo release was at the end of 1993 in collaboration with the British dance duo Spooky on a cover of the Throbbing Gristle song 'Persuasion'.

"Honey" debuted stateside courtesy of Nervous Records four years later.
"Bright Lights Fading" appeared on Slam's Year Zero album.
The Opiates made their live debut at Rough Trade, Brick Lane, London, in March, to coincide with the group's first release, the Anatomy of a Plastic Girl EP.
A second EP from The Opiates, titled Rainy Days and Remixes, was released in September 2011 as a prelude to their album Hollywood Under The Knife.
In September, Martin released a limited edition DVD entitled Five Takes (A Song About Andy), featuring five movies inspired by Andy Warhol‘s Screen Tests.
